revision.text:
The '''ATLAS-TIM AT 32''' was the process computer developed by [[Mihajlo Pupin Institute]] in Belgrade in the 1980s. The designers were Dr Vukasin Masnikosa, Dr Bozidar Levi, Mr Milenko Nikolic and their associates. Professor Bozidar Levi with 2 coauthors got the Nikola Tesla award for his ATLAS design in 1988 (see Fig.1). [[File:ATLAS MAX.jpg|right|mini|150px|Process Computer ATLAS AT 32]]
The [[SCADA]] (Supervisory, Control And Data Acquisition) [[software]] systems, such as SCADA VIEW 6000 and SCADA VIEW2, were used in many Serbian Hydro- and Termal- Power plants(ref.Lit.#1). The SCADA [[computer hardware|hardware]] developed and manufactured in the M. Pupin Institute includes ATLAS AT 32 (with [[Intel 386]] [[microprocessor]]s and [[VLSI]] circuitry), ATLAS MAX PLC ([[Intel 486]]), ATLAS MTU, Programmable controllers TIMKO (ref.Lit.#2), Atlas-2000, ATLAS XP, ATLAS-NANO, pico-ATLAS modular RTU devices etc.(for details see: ref.Lit.#3 and #4).
==References== {{inline|date=March 2016}} {{reflist}} ;Notes # V.Batanovic, J.Kon(Ed): IMP Riznica znanja, pp.&nbsp;19–24, IMP-PKS, Belgrade 2006. # D.Milicevic, D Hristovic(Ed): Racunari TIM (TIM Computers),pp.&nbsp;205–209, Naucna Knjiga, Belgrade 1990. # D.Becejski-Vujaklija, N.Markovic (Ed): 50 godina racunarstva u Srbiji (50 Years of Computing in Serbia),pp.&nbsp;123–131, DIS, IMP and PC Press, Belgrade 2011. In Serbian.
