{{For |the demographic group |Generation Z}} {{Infobox computer hardware bus | name = Gen-Z | fullname = | image = Gen-Z Consortium Logo.png | image_size = 200px | alt = Logo of the Gen-Z Consortium | caption = | invent-date = 2016 | invent-name = Gen-Z Consortium | super-name = | super-date = | replaces = | width = | numdev = | speed = | style = | hotplug = | external = | website = http://genzconsortium.org/ }}
The '''Gen-Z''' consortium is a trade group of technology vendors involved in designing [[CPU]]s, [[Random-access memory|random access memory]], servers, storage, and accelerators. The goal was an open and royalty-free "memory-semantic" protocol, which is not limited by the memory controller of a CPU. The basic operations consist of simple loads and stores with the addition of modular extensions. It is intended to be used in a switched fabric or point-to-point where each device connects using a standard connector.<ref name="self">{{Cite web |url= http://genzconsortium.org |title= Gen-Z Consortium |work= Group's web site |access-date= March 31, 2017 }}</ref>
The consortium was publicly announced on October 11, 2016.<ref name="iDG16"/> Server vendor members include [[Cray]], [[Dell Technologies]], [[Hewlett Packard Enterprise]], [[Huawei]], [[IBM]], and [[Lenovo]]. CPU vendor members include [[Advanced Micro Devices]], [[ARM Holdings]], [[Broadcom Limited]], [[Cavium]] and IBM. Memory and storage vendor members include [[Micron Technology]], [[Samsung]], [[Seagate Technology]], [[SK Hynix]], and [[Western Digital]]. Other members include [[IDT Corporation]], [[Mellanox Technologies]], [[Microsemi]], [[Red Hat]], and [[Xilinx]].<ref name="self" /> Analysts noted the absence of [[Intel]] (which announced an inter-connect technology of its own called [[Omni-Path]] a year before), Nvidia (with its own [[NVLink]] technology),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tallis|first1=Billy|title=Gen-Z Core Specification 1.0 Published|url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/12431/genz-interconnect-core-specification-10-published|accessdate=21 February 2018|publisher=Anandtech|date=13 February 2018}}</ref> and [[Cisco Systems]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= HPE, IBM, ARM, Samsung and pals in plot to weave 'memory fabric': Everyone but Intel and Cisco working together to build storage-class memory |date= October 11, 2016 |author= Chris Mellor |work= The Register |url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/10/11/memory_fabric_needed_for_storageclass_memory/ |access-date= March 30, 2017 }}</ref><ref name="iDG16">{{Cite news |title= Hardware makers unite to challenge Intel with Gen-Z spec |author= Agam Shah |date= October 11, 2016 |work= CIO from IDG |url= http://www.cio.com/article/3130273/hardware-makers-unite-to-challenge-intel-with-gen-z-spec.html |access-date= March 30, 2017 }}</ref> Some of the vendors also joined a group to promote the [[Cache coherent interconnect for accelerators]] (CCIX) protocol on the same day.<ref>{{Cite web |title= How do AMBA, CCIX and GenZ address the needs of the data center? |date= October 11, 2016 |author= Jeff Defilippi |work= ARM Community blog |url= https://community.arm.com/processors/b/blog/posts/how-do-amba-ccix-and-genz-address-the-needs-of-the-data-center |access-date= March 30, 2017 }}</ref> At about the same time, yet another consortium formed to work on an open specification for the [[Coherent Accelerator Processor Interface]] (CAPI).<ref>{{Cite news |title= Why OpenCAPI is a declaration of interconnect fabric war: Any standard but Intel in another CPU-memory interconnect consortium |date= October 14, 2016 |author= Chris Mellor |work= The Register |url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/10/14/opencapi_declaration_of_interconect_war/ |access-date= March 30, 2017 }}</ref> The efforts followed years of delays before products were available with version 4.0 of [[PCI Express]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= New PCI Express 4.0 delay may empower next-gen alternatives |author= Evan Koblentz |date=February 3, 2017 |work= Tech Republic |url= http://www.techrepublic.com/article/new-pci-express-4-0-delay-may-empower-next-gen-alternatives/ |access-date= March 31, 2017 }}</ref>
