{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox NRHP | name =R.R. Donnelley and Sons Co. Calumet Plant | nrhp_type = | designated_other1_name= Chicago Landmark | designated_other1_date= March 31, 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/LandmarksWeb/landmarkDetail.do?lanID=1547|title=R. R. Donnelley & Sons Co. Calumet Plant|publisher=City of Chicago Dept. of Pl. and Devpmt., Landmarks Div.|date=2003|accessdate=2007-08-04}}</ref> | designated_other1_abbr= CL | designated_other1_link= Chicago Landmark | designated_other1_color= #aaccff | image = Calumet Plant R R Donnelly and Sons Company B Chicago IL.jpg | caption = | location= 350 E [[Cermak Road]] [[Chicago, Illinois]] | coordinates = {{coord|41|51|13|N|87|37|5|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Chicago#Illinois#USA | area = | built = 1912 to 1929<ref>{{cite web|title=The Most Powerful Building|url=http://chiefengineer.org/?p=2478|publisher=The Chief Engineer|accessdate=2011-09-28|date=April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=350 East Cermak Road : Chicago Data Center|url=http://www.digitalrealtytrust.com/datacenters/Chicago/14/71/|publisher=Digital Realty Trust|accessdate=2008-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lakeside Press Building, Chicago|url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu?id=lakesidepressbuilding-chicago-il-usa|publisher=Emporis.com|accessdate=2008-10-27}}</ref> | architect= [[Howard Van Doren Shaw]], [[Charles Zeller Klauder]] | architecture= English Gothic | added = February 17, 1983 | governing_body = | refnum=83000308 }}
The '''R.R Donnelley Printing Plant''', sometimes known as the '''Calumet Plant''' or the '''Lakeside Plant''' and now known as the '''Lakeside Technology Center''', was built between 1912 and 1929 to house the operations of the [[RR Donnelley]] printing company. The building supported printing operations for the company and was the Donnelley headquarters until 1991 when they moved the headquarters to [[77 West Wacker Drive|77 West Wacker]]. In 1993, the plant was closed after the discontinuation by [[Sears, Roebuck and Co.]] of its [[mail-order catalog]], which had been the last major account printed there. In 1999 the building was retrofitted and is currently owned by [[Digital Realty Trust, Inc.|Digital Realty Trust]] operating as a [[Colocation centre|carrier hotel]] or [[data center]]. The newly outfitted building was the first and largest planned carrier hotel in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Feature-Lakeside Tech Center|url=http://www.progressiveengineer.com/pewebbackissues2004/PEWeb%2048%20Mar%2004-2/Lakeside.htm|publisher=Progressive Engineer|accessdate=2008-10-27}}</ref>
The building was designed by [[Howard Van Doren Shaw]] to be a fireproof design of poured [[reinforced concrete]] columns and an open-shell concrete floor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Serving, Saving & Saluting the South Loop|url=http://www.lib.colum.edu/archhistory/shaw.htm|publisher=Columbia College Chicago|accessdate=2008-10-27}}</ref> Although considered to be expensive by the standards of that time, [[T.E. Donnelley]] agreed that the support would be needed for the many tons of paper they used and large presses they operated. Supported by 4,675 steel-[[reinforced concrete column]]s, this type of construction not only served the Donnelly well, it also provided the perfect infrastructure for future tenants. To further the building's support structure, reinforcing bars, normally laid perpendicular, were laid at various angles enabling the floors to bear loads of at least 250 pounds per square foot.
Current major tenants of the building include the [[Chicago Mercantile Exchange]], [[Telx]], [[Equinix]], [[Steadfast Networks]] and [[Qwest]].
Exterior ornaments depict symbols of printing history. Portions of the building, including the interior Memorial Library, were designed by architect [[Charles Klauder]].
