{{More footnotes|date=September 2013}}
In [[Computer programming|programming]] [[jargon]], '''Yoda conditions''' (also called ''Yoda notation'') is a [[programming style]] where the two parts of an expression are reversed from the typical order in a [[Conditional (computer programming)|conditional statement]]. A Yoda condition places the constant portion of the expression on the left side of the conditional statement. The name for this programming style is derived from the ''[[Star Wars]]'' character named [[Yoda]], who [[Yoda#Character_overview|speaks English with non-standard grammar]].

Yoda conditions are part of the [[Symfony]] coding standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://symfony.com/doc/current/contributing/code/standards.html#structure |title=Coding Standards (Contributing to Symfony) |website=Symfony.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-12}}</ref>

== Example ==
Usually a conditional statement would be written as:
<source lang="java">
if ($value == 42) { /* ... */ }
// Reads like: "If the value is equal to 42..."
</source>

Yoda conditions describe the same expression, but reversed:
<source lang="java">
if (42 == $value) { /* ... */ }
// Reads like: "If 42 equals the value..."
</source>

The constant is written to the left of the [[Relational operator|comparison operator]], and the variable whose value is being checked against the constant is written to the right. This order is comparable to the non-standard speaking style of Yoda, which is roughly [[object–subject–verb]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pullum|first1=Geoffrey K.|title=Yoda's Syntax the Tribune Analyzes; Supply More Details I Will!|url=http://itre.cis.upenn.edu/~myl/languagelog/archives/002173.html|website=Itre.cis.upenn.edu|publisher=Language Log|accessdate=2014-12-22|date=2005-05-18|quote=One way to look at Yoda's syntax is that it shows signs of favoring OSV syntax (Object-Subject-Verb) as the basic order in the simple clause.}}</ref> (e.g., “When nine hundred years old you reach, look as good you will not."<ref>{{cite web|title=The StarWars.com 10: Best Yoda Quotes|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/the-starwars-com-10-best-yoda-quotes|website=starwars.com|publisher=Lucasfilm, Ltd.|accessdate=2014-12-22|date=2013-11-26|quote=When nine hundred years old you reach, look as good you will not.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Quotes for Yoda (Character)|url=https://www.imdb.com/character/ch0000015/quotes|website=imdb.com|publisher=Amazon|accessdate=2014-12-22|quote=When nine hundred years old *you* reach, look as good *you* will not, hmm?}}</ref>).

== Advantage ==
Placing the constant value in the expression does not change the behavior of the [[Computer program|program]] (unless the values evaluate to false—see below). In programming languages that use a single [[equals sign]] (<code>=</code>) for [[Assignment (computer science)|assignment]] and not for comparison, a possible [[Assignment (computer science)#Assignment versus equality|mistake]] is to assign a value unintentionally instead of writing a conditional statement.

<source lang="java">
if (myNumber = 42) { /* ... */ }
// This assigns 42 to myNumber instead of evaluating the desired condition
</source>
Using Yoda conditions:
<source lang="java">
if (42 = myNumber) { /* ... */ }
// This is a syntax error and will not compile
</source>

Since 42 is a [[constant (programming)|constant]] and can not be changed, this error will be [[Compile time|caught]] by the [[compiler]].

<source lang="java">
Boolean myBoolean = true;
if (myBoolean = null) { /* ... */ }
// This causes a NullPointerException in Java Runtime, but legal in compilation.
</source>

It can also avoid some types of unsafe null behavior.

<source lang="java">
String myString = null;
if (myString.equals("foobar")) { /* ... */ }
// This causes a NullPointerException in Java
</source>

With Yoda conditions:
<source lang="java">
String myString = null;
if ("foobar".equals(myString)) { /* ... */ }
// This is false, as expected
</source>

== Criticism ==
Critics of Yoda conditions see the lack of readability as a disadvantage that outweighs the benefits described above. Some programming languages as Python and Swift do not allow variable assignments within conditionals, by defining that assignments do not return a value, in which case this error is impossible to make.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://developer.apple.com/library/ios/documentation/Swift/Conceptual/Swift_Programming_Language/BasicOperators.html |title=The Swift Programming Language (Swift 3.0.1): Basic Operators |website=Developer.apple.com |date=2016-10-27 |accessdate=2016-11-12}}</ref>  Many compilers produce a warning for code such as <code>if (myNumber = 42)</code> (e.g., the [[GNU Compiler Collection|GCC]] <code>-Wall</code> option warns ''suggest parentheses around assignment used as truth value''), which alerts the programmer to the likely mistake. In dynamic languages like [[JavaScript]], [[Lint_(software)|linters]] such as ESLint can warn on assignment inside a conditional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eslint.org/docs/rules/no-cond-assign |title=disallow assignment operators in conditional statements |website=eslint.org |accessdate=2017-02-17}}</ref>

The advantage of avoiding null behavior can also be considered a disadvantage, as null pointer errors can be hidden and only appear much later in the program.

Another disadvantage appears in C++ when comparing non-basic types as the == is an operator and there may not be a suitable overloaded operator function defined. Example: a Microsoft's <code>CComBSTR</code> compare against a [[string literal]], written as <code>if (L"Hello" == cbstrMessage)</code>, does not map to an overload function.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cfy54764.aspx |title=CComBSTR::operator |website=Msdn.microsoft.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-12}}</ref>

